00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:32.140
PROFESSOR: In a way, I would
say most of this course up

00:00:32.140 --> 00:00:34.920
until today, or maybe the memory
lecture, was about how

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:37.310
brilliant the human
mind and brain is.

00:00:37.310 --> 00:00:40.520
How the visual system is so
brilliant nobody can make a

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:42.910
machine that sees so well.

00:00:42.910 --> 00:00:45.260
We didn't talk too much
about physical action.

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:47.820
But how we move in the world,
how we act upon the world,

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:50.320
there's no robot that can
compete with you.

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:53.260
Language is far beyond computers
to be nearly as

00:00:53.260 --> 00:00:56.410
sophisticated as you are,
as a five-year-old is.

00:00:56.410 --> 00:01:00.400
So in all those domains, we
mostly think about in terms of

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:04.280
psychology or brain function,
how is it that we're endowed

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:06.680
with such amazing capacities?

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:09.760
When it comes to thinking, one
of the highest forms of human

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:13.200
activity, thinking, hard problem
solving, edges of

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:17.120
creativity, that kinds of thing,
it's something we have

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:20.690
a huge respect for, something we
wish for, something that we

00:01:20.690 --> 00:01:22.990
know is a very, very
valuable tool.

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:24.650
But psychologists have
emphasized the

00:01:24.650 --> 00:01:26.400
traps we can fall in.

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:28.510
I mean in a way what's easy
for us is what the brain

00:01:28.510 --> 00:01:30.010
empowers in us.

00:01:30.010 --> 00:01:32.410
It's easy for us to recognize
objects or faces

00:01:32.410 --> 00:01:34.580
or move in the world.

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:37.270
When we feel something is hard,
like thinking hard, for

00:01:37.270 --> 00:01:40.840
problem sets or global warming
or other things that are hard

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:44.960
to think about, then we know
that we're sort of leaving the

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:47.830
apparatus that's easy for us
and we're entering into a

00:01:47.830 --> 00:01:51.980
hazardous, difficult form
of our mental lives.

00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:55.520
So, I'm going to show you
a video for a moment.

00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:57.840
Because the other fun thing is,
and maybe this is true of

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:02.430
all of us in different ways, all
the time, we often don't

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:05.040
recognize, we often don't
recognize when we're thinking

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:07.000
not as well as we might.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.080
So this is a trap.

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:12.590
So I'm going to show you, the
original punking TV show, this

00:02:12.590 --> 00:02:13.540
was called Candid Camera.

00:02:13.540 --> 00:02:14.170
It's pretty old.

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:15.535
So this is a clip from there.

00:02:15.535 --> 00:02:19.090
And here's a couple people asked
to do a school problem,

00:02:19.090 --> 00:02:22.350
7/8 divided by 3/4 and
how many square

00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:23.840
feet in a square yard?

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:26.940
And what's kind of funny about
it in my mind is, not only

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:31.120
that the people are wrong, but
how wrong they are and how

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:33.539
much they don't realize
sometimes how wrong they are.

00:02:40.250 --> 00:02:46.040
I mean what's impressive about
this is that not only are the

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:48.580
people wrong, but they don't
say like, I forget.

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:51.740
They just start to give answers,
throwing out numbers.

00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:54.970
And so how different are
all of us in that?

00:02:54.970 --> 00:02:57.800
So some of these again
are on the internet.

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:00.540
And this is an MIT audience,
which is about the hardest

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:01.530
audience to pull this off.

00:03:01.530 --> 00:03:05.430
And at Stanford, I could pull
this off much better.

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:08.440
So some of these won't go as
easily as they might for other

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:09.240
typical audiences.

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:10.210
Here we go.

00:03:10.210 --> 00:03:12.110
Two train stations are a
hundred miles apart.

00:03:12.110 --> 00:03:15.130
At 2:00 PM one Saturday
afternoon, the two trains

00:03:15.130 --> 00:03:16.900
start toward each other,
one from each station.

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:18.366
One travels at 60 miles
an hour, the other

00:03:18.366 --> 00:03:19.080
at 40 miles an hour.

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:20.920
Just as the trains pulls out
of their stations, a bird

00:03:20.920 --> 00:03:23.260
springs into the air in front of
the first train, and flies

00:03:23.260 --> 00:03:24.480
ahead to the front
of the second.

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:26.530
When the bird reaches the
second, it turns back, without

00:03:26.530 --> 00:03:28.180
losing any speed, and
flies directly

00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:28.970
toward the first step.

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:30.630
Doesn't this remind you of all
the high school physics

00:03:30.630 --> 00:03:32.120
problems you had earlier?

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:33.710
Where's the frictionless
pulley?

00:03:33.710 --> 00:03:35.720
The bird continues to fly back
and forth between the trains

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:36.730
at 80 miles an hour.

00:03:36.730 --> 00:03:38.210
How many miles will the
bird have flown

00:03:38.210 --> 00:03:41.000
before the trains meet?

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:42.230
It's a little bit of a trick.

00:03:42.230 --> 00:03:47.000
Because the answer is told to
you directly, pretty much.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:48.450
So 100 miles apart.

00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:51.635
How long will it take for the
trains to reach each other, if

00:03:51.635 --> 00:03:54.630
one is 60 miles an hour and
one is 40 miles an hour?

00:03:54.630 --> 00:03:55.130
AUDIENCE: Hour.

00:03:55.130 --> 00:03:56.720
PROFESSOR: Hour.

00:03:56.720 --> 00:03:59.220
So how many miles an hour
does the bird fly?

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:01.250
AUDIENCE: 80.

00:04:01.250 --> 00:04:02.500
Easier than you think.

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:08.020
So those are the kinds of ones I
just showed that people kind

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:09.750
of get themselves into
their thinking cap.

00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:11.130
And it's a trick.

00:04:11.130 --> 00:04:12.900
Here we go.

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:15.010
I need somebody who is willing
to, at their chair,

00:04:15.010 --> 00:04:16.260
just call out words.

00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:23.410
Thank you very much.

00:04:23.410 --> 00:04:23.990
Here we go.

00:04:23.990 --> 00:04:25.440
In English, many words are
pronounced somewhat

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:27.170
differently depending on the
way they are spelled.

00:04:27.170 --> 00:04:28.330
But here we go.

00:04:28.330 --> 00:04:32.270
Can you give me a synonym for
people or family, a word that

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:35.630
people would often
say for that?

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:37.410
I'll give you one.

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:39.590
Folk.

00:04:39.590 --> 00:04:40.810
Now, I know this is
a history quiz.

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:42.020
But I'll help you.

00:04:42.020 --> 00:04:44.000
I wouldn't know the answer
to this, necessarily.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:45.940
Can you give me the name of an
American president at the time

00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:46.690
of the Mexican War?

00:04:46.690 --> 00:04:47.240
And I'll give you a hint.

00:04:47.240 --> 00:04:48.595
It rhymes with folk.

00:04:48.595 --> 00:04:49.240
AUDIENCE: Polk.

00:04:49.240 --> 00:04:49.940
PROFESSOR: Polk.

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:51.020
Everybody can help.

00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:51.650
Everybody help.

00:04:51.650 --> 00:04:53.330
One, two, three.

00:04:53.330 --> 00:04:55.620
Can you give me the name of the
word that means egg white?

00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:56.564
AUDIENCE: Yolk.

00:04:56.564 --> 00:04:58.520
PROFESSOR: Aha.

00:04:58.520 --> 00:04:58.960
No.

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:00.380
Is the yolk, the egg white?

00:05:03.050 --> 00:05:03.530
I know.

00:05:03.530 --> 00:05:04.580
It's a pretty hilarious course.

00:05:04.580 --> 00:05:06.240
Thank you.

00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:08.690
So this is an example
of what people

00:05:08.690 --> 00:05:10.880
call functional fixedness.

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:12.990
Your mind is going
a certain way.

00:05:12.990 --> 00:05:14.470
And you're on a certain pace.

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:16.280
And all of a sudden when you
need to put the mental break

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:19.710
on, your habit of thought takes
you a slightly wrong

00:05:19.710 --> 00:05:21.190
direction, on a very
superficial test.

00:05:21.190 --> 00:05:24.110
Thank you very much.

00:05:24.110 --> 00:05:26.330
Here's an experiment.

00:05:26.330 --> 00:05:29.470
In 10 minutes, only about 39%
of people solve this.

00:05:29.470 --> 00:05:31.020
You go into a room like this.

00:05:31.020 --> 00:05:33.470
The strings are too far apart.

00:05:33.470 --> 00:05:34.810
You have stuff around here.

00:05:34.810 --> 00:05:36.670
And your job to tie the
strings together.

00:05:36.670 --> 00:05:37.920
What do you do?

00:05:40.870 --> 00:05:42.750
AUDIENCE: Stand on the chair?

00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:44.620
PROFESSOR: Standing on the chair
is an interesting one.

00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:46.830
Let's pretend it doesn't work.

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:47.770
It wouldn't.

00:05:47.770 --> 00:05:50.020
It would get you up, but they'd
be far apart still.

00:05:50.020 --> 00:05:50.660
It could.

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:53.400
Let's pretend it doesn't.

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:54.660
You'd have to be there,
to be convinced.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:54.930
You know what I mean.

00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:56.180
It mean depends on the angle.

00:05:58.610 --> 00:05:59.790
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:05:59.790 --> 00:06:00.115
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:06:00.115 --> 00:06:01.340
AUDIENCE: Tie it to the end.

00:06:01.340 --> 00:06:02.930
PROFESSOR: Ah.

00:06:02.930 --> 00:06:05.490
So you're one of the 39%.

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:08.850
So the idea is, if you tie for
example, the pliers onto the

00:06:08.850 --> 00:06:12.680
thing and get it swinging, you
could catch it, right?

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:17.770
So why don't people come up with
that answer very easily?

00:06:17.770 --> 00:06:21.390
PROFESSOR: Because what
are pliers for?

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:23.180
Pliering.

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:25.840
They're not for swinging
ropes.

00:06:25.840 --> 00:06:28.820
So again, the word they use
is functional fixedness.

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:30.680
You know what a plier is for.

00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:35.390
It doesn't seem like a good
candidate to do this job.

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:35.830
Here's another one.

00:06:35.830 --> 00:06:38.270
You walk into a room and there's
a door that's closed

00:06:38.270 --> 00:06:39.180
behind you.

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:40.430
And you see these things
on a table.

00:06:40.430 --> 00:06:42.310
And you're asked, could
you support this

00:06:42.310 --> 00:06:45.290
candle on the door?

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:49.780
About 23% of people
get this, in 1945.

00:06:49.780 --> 00:06:51.590
What do you do?

00:06:51.590 --> 00:06:54.220
This is just like all
the spy movies.

00:06:54.220 --> 00:06:55.944
Yes?

00:06:55.944 --> 00:06:57.194
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:59.450 --> 00:06:59.875
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:06:59.875 --> 00:07:01.515
AUDIENCE: Put the tacks through
the width of the door.

00:07:01.515 --> 00:07:02.570
PROFESSOR: Yeah, through
the width of door

00:07:02.570 --> 00:07:03.790
would be pretty good.

00:07:03.790 --> 00:07:05.380
It's not really supporting
the candle, but it

00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:06.230
could get the job done.

00:07:06.230 --> 00:07:07.130
That's not a bad thought.

00:07:07.130 --> 00:07:08.350
These are all good thoughts.

00:07:08.350 --> 00:07:10.090
If it were me, I wouldn't
be close.

00:07:10.090 --> 00:07:11.300
So that's better than I do.

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:11.980
Yeah?

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:14.740
AUDIENCE: Take out the tacks
and then tack the base.

00:07:14.740 --> 00:07:16.300
PROFESSOR: Have you
see this before?

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:16.690
No.

00:07:16.690 --> 00:07:17.410
Excellent.

00:07:17.410 --> 00:07:21.060
As I tell you, MIT's audience
is not an easy audience.

00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:25.230
The idea is that you dump the
tacks, and then stick the tack

00:07:25.230 --> 00:07:26.900
into the back of
the empty box.

00:07:26.900 --> 00:07:28.820
Nice platform for a candle.

00:07:28.820 --> 00:07:32.520
Why don't most people
think about that?

00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:36.650
Because what's the
job of the box?

00:07:36.650 --> 00:07:39.060
To hold the tacks.

00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:40.610
My job is to figure
out this problem.

00:07:40.610 --> 00:07:42.820
You hang on to the tacks.

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:45.330
And in fact if they do the same
experiment, but just put

00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:48.070
the tacks next to the
box, a lot of people

00:07:48.070 --> 00:07:49.350
get it right away.

00:07:49.350 --> 00:07:52.650
Because now that box, it's
yearning to support something.

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:53.570
It no longer has a job.

00:07:53.570 --> 00:07:56.360
It's an unemployed box that you
can stick onto the door

00:07:56.360 --> 00:07:57.530
and support this.

00:07:57.530 --> 00:08:01.140
Your mind just gets stuck with
thinking the box is a holder.

00:08:01.140 --> 00:08:02.390
It's not a platform.

00:08:04.870 --> 00:08:06.810
This is the original-- and
you've seen this so

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:07.370
many times by now.

00:08:07.370 --> 00:08:09.860
This is one of the original,
thinking outside of the box

00:08:09.860 --> 00:08:12.500
things, where you're supposed to
connect the dots with four

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:14.065
straight lines without
lifting a pencil.

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:23.140
Some of you know this.

00:08:23.140 --> 00:08:24.430
Some of you are figuring
out on the spot.

00:08:24.430 --> 00:08:26.830
But I'll just show you.

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:28.155
So there's an answer.

00:08:28.155 --> 00:08:30.840
The other ones are similar.

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:33.140
Why do so many people
get stuck in this

00:08:33.140 --> 00:08:34.600
and not get it done?

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:36.980
Because they don't
like this part.

00:08:36.980 --> 00:08:38.760
And they don't like this
part, because it's

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:41.520
drawing outside the box.

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:43.350
They're always looking for the
connections within the box.

00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:45.870
And it seems cheating in some
sense to draw outside the box.

00:08:45.870 --> 00:08:48.740
There's an intuition, like with
the box with the tacks,

00:08:48.740 --> 00:08:50.610
that you're supposed
to stay in there.

00:08:50.610 --> 00:08:54.450
So if they get no information
in this study, practically

00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:58.140
nobody solved it,
in a given time.

00:08:58.140 --> 00:08:59.830
If they get a hint, you
can draw outside the

00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:01.470
square, that helps.

00:09:01.470 --> 00:09:04.080
But then, outside the square
puts again, the first line.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:06.280
They're still only half
the time getting it.

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:07.740
Because you've got to go
outside a second time.

00:09:07.740 --> 00:09:10.420
So it gets a lot of information
to get comfortable

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:13.470
with finding a way to do this
that's completely within the

00:09:13.470 --> 00:09:16.410
rules, but not the way you
intuitively feel might be the

00:09:16.410 --> 00:09:17.840
right way to do it.

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:21.170
So those are all examples of
functional fixedness, where

00:09:21.170 --> 00:09:23.620
you have a certain belief about
what's going on and it's

00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:27.670
hard to overcome that to solve
a problem in a novel way.

00:09:27.670 --> 00:09:29.950
Another thing that people think
about as the way to

00:09:29.950 --> 00:09:32.130
overcome some of these problems
of thinking about

00:09:32.130 --> 00:09:36.790
problems is different
representations that let you

00:09:36.790 --> 00:09:38.850
take a different look at
a problem to be solved.

00:09:38.850 --> 00:09:40.700
So picture a large
piece of paper, a

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:42.050
hundredth of an inch thick.

00:09:42.050 --> 00:09:43.690
Now, in your imagination,
fold it once.

00:09:43.690 --> 00:09:44.770
You have two layers.

00:09:44.770 --> 00:09:46.620
Continue to fold it on
itself 50 times.

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:48.120
It's true that's it's impossible
to fold it in

00:09:48.120 --> 00:09:50.270
place, such a piece of
paper, 50 times.

00:09:50.270 --> 00:09:52.350
But for the sake of the problem,
imagining that you

00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:55.712
can, about how thick would the
50-times-folded paper be?

00:09:55.712 --> 00:09:57.640
And everybody's first intuition
is, well, how thick

00:09:57.640 --> 00:09:58.430
can a piece of paper be?

00:09:58.430 --> 00:10:00.370
Of course, this is a
hypothetical problem, not an

00:10:00.370 --> 00:10:02.130
actual paper problem.

00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:03.660
But if you do the
math, it's big.

00:10:08.800 --> 00:10:10.150
So here's another one.

00:10:14.160 --> 00:10:16.620
One morning, exactly at sunrise,
a Buddhist monk began

00:10:16.620 --> 00:10:17.980
to climb a tall mountain.

00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:20.075
A narrow path no more than a
foot or two wide, spiraled

00:10:20.075 --> 00:10:21.430
around the mountain
to a glittering

00:10:21.430 --> 00:10:22.520
temple at the summit.

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:24.690
The monk ascended at various
rates of speed, stopping many

00:10:24.690 --> 00:10:27.240
times along the way to rest
and eat dried fruit he

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:27.710
carried with him.

00:10:27.710 --> 00:10:29.370
He reached the temple shortly
before sunset.

00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:31.350
After several days of fasting
and meditation, he began his

00:10:31.350 --> 00:10:33.920
journey back along the same
path, starting it at sunrise

00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:35.630
and again walking at variable
speeds, with many

00:10:35.630 --> 00:10:36.910
pauses along the way.

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:38.710
His average speed descending
was, of course, greater than

00:10:38.710 --> 00:10:40.280
his average climbing speed.

00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:42.700
Show that there's a spot along
the path that the monk will

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:44.320
occupy on both trips
at precisely the

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:46.020
same time of day.

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:48.050
So that sounds moderately
hard.

00:10:48.050 --> 00:10:50.610
But if you draw the
picture, so we

00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:51.630
went and get an equation.

00:10:51.630 --> 00:10:53.860
Now, we have a pictorial
representation.

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:57.010
You can see there has to be some
moment of the ascending

00:10:57.010 --> 00:10:59.450
and descending path that
cross in time.

00:10:59.450 --> 00:11:00.820
You don't know what
it's going to be.

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:02.600
But there has to be some
moment in time.

00:11:02.600 --> 00:11:03.700
And maybe that's obvious.

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:05.840
But for a lot of people it seems
stunningly complicated

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:07.025
that you could even
demonstrate that

00:11:07.025 --> 00:11:09.040
in any way at all.

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:10.880
Here's one you could
think about.

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:13.620
Suppose you are a doctor faced
with a patient who has a

00:11:13.620 --> 00:11:15.190
malignant tumor in
his stomach.

00:11:15.190 --> 00:11:17.340
It's impossible to operate on
the tumor, but unless the

00:11:17.340 --> 00:11:19.440
tumor is destroyed the
patient will die.

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:21.660
There's a kind of ray that can
be used to destroy the tumor.

00:11:21.660 --> 00:11:24.860
If the rays reach the tumor all
at once, with sufficiently

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:26.680
high intensity, the tumor
will be destroyed.

00:11:26.680 --> 00:11:30.350
Unfortunately, at this high
intensity the healthy tissue

00:11:30.350 --> 00:11:33.240
that the rays pass through,
will also be destroyed.

00:11:33.240 --> 00:11:35.860
At lower intensity, the rays
are harmless to healthy

00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:38.570
tissue, but they don't affect
the tumor either.

00:11:38.570 --> 00:11:40.860
What type of procedure might be
used to destroy the tumor

00:11:40.860 --> 00:11:43.910
with the rays, and at the same
time avoid destroying the

00:11:43.910 --> 00:11:44.820
healthy tissue?

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:47.050
Now, if you know the answer to
this, don't jump right up.

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:48.820
Give other people a few
moments to puzzle.

00:11:53.370 --> 00:11:57.760
About 10% of people solve this
in a small unit of time,

00:11:57.760 --> 00:11:59.010
before the Internet.

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:06.180
And so, what's the answer
though, for those of you?

00:12:06.180 --> 00:12:07.950
Yeah, I see some
hands, I think.

00:12:07.950 --> 00:12:08.270
Go ahead.

00:12:08.270 --> 00:12:09.920
Did you want to say?

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:10.410
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:10.530
PROFESSOR: No.

00:12:10.530 --> 00:12:11.385
Exactly at the spot, sir.

00:12:11.385 --> 00:12:12.780
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:12.780 --> 00:12:13.430
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:12:13.430 --> 00:12:17.350
Have several weak ones aimed
to converge at the tumor.

00:12:17.350 --> 00:12:19.290
I saw your hands.

00:12:19.290 --> 00:12:21.170
So the idea is to have several
different rays, each of which

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:22.740
are weak enough not to
destroy the tissue.

00:12:22.740 --> 00:12:24.930
But when they converge spatially
at the tumor, they

00:12:24.930 --> 00:12:27.400
would sum enough to
destroy the tumor.

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:29.840
That's the problem-solving
answer to this.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:33.990
So knowing that, here's another
kind of a problem.

00:12:33.990 --> 00:12:36.390
A dictator ruled a small country
from a fortress.

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:38.750
The fortress was situated in the
middle of the country and

00:12:38.750 --> 00:12:40.420
many roads radiated
outward from it,

00:12:40.420 --> 00:12:42.670
like spokes in a wheel.

00:12:42.670 --> 00:12:44.740
A great general vowed to capture
the fortress and free

00:12:44.740 --> 00:12:46.080
the country of the dictator.

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:47.810
The general knew that if the
entire army could attack the

00:12:47.810 --> 00:12:49.320
fortress at once, it
could be captured.

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:52.300
But a spy reported that the
dictator had planted mines on

00:12:52.300 --> 00:12:53.380
each of the roads.

00:12:53.380 --> 00:12:55.630
The mines were set so that small
bodies of men could pass

00:12:55.630 --> 00:12:58.180
over them safely, since dictator
needed to be able to

00:12:58.180 --> 00:13:00.000
move troops and workers about.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.610
However, any large force would
detonate the mines.

00:13:02.610 --> 00:13:04.320
Not only would this blow up
the road, but the dictator

00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:06.860
would destroy many villages
in retaliation.

00:13:06.860 --> 00:13:09.050
A full-scale, direct attack
on the fortress seemed

00:13:09.050 --> 00:13:11.250
impossible.

00:13:11.250 --> 00:13:13.270
Does this problem remind you of
the other problem, I mean

00:13:13.270 --> 00:13:15.190
back-to-back, like this?

00:13:15.190 --> 00:13:17.130
He divided his army up
into small groups.

00:13:17.130 --> 00:13:20.520
Now, they're small enough per
path into the castle.

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:22.320
And they converge on the
castle, like the X-rays

00:13:22.320 --> 00:13:24.260
converged on the tumor.

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:26.000
So this is reasoning
by analogy.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:27.170
We have problem solving
approach.

00:13:27.170 --> 00:13:29.000
Divide your resources
spatially.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.270
Have them meet at the same time,
and converge in a way

00:13:31.270 --> 00:13:32.310
that's effective.

00:13:32.310 --> 00:13:34.750
So what you might call the deep
structure of the problem

00:13:34.750 --> 00:13:36.760
is the same, with the surface
story being different.

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:40.280
One is tumors and treatments.

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:41.690
But there's a strict analogy.

00:13:41.690 --> 00:13:44.400
Capturing the castle is like
destroying the tumor.

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:47.290
The fortress is like the tumor
that you want to get to.

00:13:47.290 --> 00:13:48.710
The army is like the
rays and the

00:13:48.710 --> 00:13:50.250
general is like the doctor.

00:13:50.250 --> 00:13:53.650
So if it is back-to-back like
this, where I just said,

00:13:53.650 --> 00:13:55.280
here's a problem.

00:13:55.280 --> 00:13:57.430
And here's a problem
just like that.

00:13:57.430 --> 00:14:01.300
Everybody says, well, send the
troops on the different paths

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:03.660
and have them converge
at the same time.

00:14:03.660 --> 00:14:06.590
If you don't say that though, if
you don't tell people this

00:14:06.590 --> 00:14:08.010
is the same, use
the same rule.

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:11.160
If you don't tell people that,
only about a third come up

00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:12.460
with it spontaneously.

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:14.920
If you just make a little bit
of an effort not to make it

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:17.610
completely obvious that
it's the same problem.

00:14:17.610 --> 00:14:18.860
You just wait a little bit.

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:25.030
So the surface differences,
the war story versus the

00:14:25.030 --> 00:14:29.120
medical story, will mostly throw
people from recognizing

00:14:29.120 --> 00:14:30.220
the analogies.

00:14:30.220 --> 00:14:33.320
People recognize surface
analogies all the time.

00:14:33.320 --> 00:14:35.690
If we have war in the Middle
East now, from the US

00:14:35.690 --> 00:14:40.240
perspective there's analogies
to Vietnam, a war and a war.

00:14:40.240 --> 00:14:42.540
But other kinds of analogies
across situations, people have

00:14:42.540 --> 00:14:46.740
a hard time mapping, if the
surfaces look different.

00:14:46.740 --> 00:14:50.140
And here's an example where they
gave people two problems

00:14:50.140 --> 00:14:53.410
of a certain kind.

00:14:53.410 --> 00:14:55.720
And they said as part of the
experiment, and here's a

00:14:55.720 --> 00:14:56.800
classroom demonstration.

00:14:56.800 --> 00:14:59.620
If it's immediate, they
sort of get it.

00:14:59.620 --> 00:15:03.390
But if they wait just a little
bit, and they move from one

00:15:03.390 --> 00:15:07.640
room to another room, they don't
apply the rule at all.

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:09.230
So it's very tricky.

00:15:09.230 --> 00:15:10.970
We would like to think well,
gee, we know all kinds of

00:15:10.970 --> 00:15:13.040
things about the world, that
we can bring in a mental

00:15:13.040 --> 00:15:16.380
toolkit to solve problems,
all kinds of ideas.

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:19.690
But if the problem doesn't look
the same as the prior

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:22.070
problem, people have a hard
time spontaneously saying,

00:15:22.070 --> 00:15:23.900
there's an answer I know, and
I can apply it to the

00:15:23.900 --> 00:15:26.520
situation, unless it's really,
really obvious.

00:15:26.520 --> 00:15:30.230
People don't transfer deep
solutions very easily across

00:15:30.230 --> 00:15:31.480
what looks like different
situations.

00:15:34.150 --> 00:15:35.020
Something different.

00:15:35.020 --> 00:15:37.530
The instructors in a flight
school adopted a policy of

00:15:37.530 --> 00:15:39.990
consistent, positive
reinforcement, recommended by

00:15:39.990 --> 00:15:40.780
psychologists.

00:15:40.780 --> 00:15:42.150
And we know we're very
suspicious about

00:15:42.150 --> 00:15:44.320
psychologists, right?

00:15:44.320 --> 00:15:47.580
But you have to imagine the
instructor went to some

00:15:47.580 --> 00:15:49.350
classroom and somebody said,
positive reinforcement

00:15:49.350 --> 00:15:50.800
is the way to go.

00:15:50.800 --> 00:15:53.480
They verbally reinforced each
successful execution of a

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:54.820
flight maneuver.

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:56.710
After some experience with this
training approach, the

00:15:56.710 --> 00:15:59.020
instructors claimed that
contrary to psychological

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:03.980
doctrine, high praise for good
execution of complex maneuvers

00:16:03.980 --> 00:16:06.480
typically result in a decrement
of performance on

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:07.880
the next try.

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:09.920
Are they correct?

00:16:09.920 --> 00:16:12.360
So you understand, you have to
have in your mind all the

00:16:12.360 --> 00:16:13.550
military movies where
there's a really

00:16:13.550 --> 00:16:15.140
tough sergeant training.

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:17.860
The other one that yells at
you to make you succeed.

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:19.830
But for half the movie, you
don't know if the sergeant

00:16:19.830 --> 00:16:21.770
will break you or make you
into a better woman or a

00:16:21.770 --> 00:16:23.000
better man.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:23.970
So he's barking orders.

00:16:23.970 --> 00:16:25.940
And some psychologist says,
well, you should really think

00:16:25.940 --> 00:16:27.520
about saying nice things to
these people, because that's

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:28.150
encouraging.

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:29.760
Errgh.

00:16:29.760 --> 00:16:31.820
Somebody does a flight
maneuver and does

00:16:31.820 --> 00:16:32.427
a really good job.

00:16:32.427 --> 00:16:33.870
And he goes, that's awesome.

00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:35.400
And then the person goes
up and does worse.

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:37.990
And he goes aargh, you're
all terrible.

00:16:37.990 --> 00:16:39.170
So what's happening?

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:40.420
Yeah.

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:53.110
AUDIENCE: It must-- the person
typically does really well.

00:16:53.110 --> 00:16:56.470
Doing really well one time isn't
indicative of really

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:56.950
well the next time.

00:16:56.950 --> 00:16:58.100
PROFESSOR: It's even worse
than that, right.

00:16:58.100 --> 00:17:00.040
So all of us have in us a
range of performance.

00:17:00.040 --> 00:17:00.660
We know that.

00:17:00.660 --> 00:17:05.430
If you do sports, if you do
research, if you do anything,

00:17:05.430 --> 00:17:07.680
some days we're at
our average.

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:08.920
Some days, we're not so good.

00:17:08.920 --> 00:17:11.480
Some days, we go wow, that
was pretty good.

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:13.910
We all have a range of
performance that's possible,

00:17:13.910 --> 00:17:16.970
our average performance, our
best days, our worst days.

00:17:16.970 --> 00:17:19.700
So you just went up
and you did an

00:17:19.700 --> 00:17:21.700
awesome flight maneuver.

00:17:21.700 --> 00:17:24.919
Is that your average one or
is that a peak example?

00:17:28.530 --> 00:17:30.330
It's a peak example.

00:17:30.330 --> 00:17:32.070
Statistically, what's the
likelihood of your next one

00:17:32.070 --> 00:17:35.020
going to be, better or worse?

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:36.270
Worse.

00:17:38.210 --> 00:17:40.930
You can't always be at your
best, because you'd sort of go

00:17:40.930 --> 00:17:43.440
into infinite excellence.

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:44.840
You have a range
of performance.

00:17:48.500 --> 00:17:49.800
In the NBA, what's a
really good score?

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:52.090
30 points is really good.

00:17:52.090 --> 00:17:53.700
That's the average though,
of the best players.

00:17:53.700 --> 00:17:55.530
They don't go out and go,
I got 30 tonight.

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:56.600
And tomorrow, I'll get 32.

00:17:56.600 --> 00:17:58.770
And by the end of the season,
I have like 180

00:17:58.770 --> 00:18:01.320
points every game.

00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:02.690
Even if you're on the
Miami Heat, you have

00:18:02.690 --> 00:18:05.190
to do a good job.

00:18:05.190 --> 00:18:08.800
So do you understand?

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:10.920
So here's another example.

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:14.340
Parents of very famous,
successful kids, are they

00:18:14.340 --> 00:18:17.680
mostly super-famous and
super-successful?

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:20.800
Or do we mostly read about them
and go whoa, that's a

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:22.050
tough deal, what
happened there?

00:18:22.050 --> 00:18:23.365
What's your impression?

00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:28.630
Let's ask this question--

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:30.950
and if you are facing
these burdens.

00:18:30.950 --> 00:18:34.155
If your parent wins a Nobel
Prize, what's the odds that

00:18:34.155 --> 00:18:36.450
you win a Nobel Prize.

00:18:36.450 --> 00:18:36.785
Small.

00:18:36.785 --> 00:18:39.530
And they go oh, the
underachieving kid.

00:18:39.530 --> 00:18:42.110
All the pressure from the parent
to do really well, with

00:18:42.110 --> 00:18:43.710
a Nobel Laureate
as your parent.

00:18:43.710 --> 00:18:44.960
Well, maybe.

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:47.360
Maybe your parent is berating
from kindergarten on saying,

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:49.820
if you don't eat your peas and
carrots, you won't win a Nobel

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:51.380
Prize, like I. That's
a possibility.

00:18:51.380 --> 00:18:53.180
We can't rule it out.

00:18:53.180 --> 00:18:55.490
But if somebody in your family
wins a Nobel Prize, what's the

00:18:55.490 --> 00:18:58.630
odds that other people in your
family will win that.

00:18:58.630 --> 00:18:58.950
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:18:58.950 --> 00:19:01.320
So we call that regression
to the mean.

00:19:01.320 --> 00:19:04.380
If you have an outstanding
example, a person who wins a

00:19:04.380 --> 00:19:09.210
Nobel Prize, everybody around
them is not likely to win.

00:19:09.210 --> 00:19:12.870
If you have an outstanding day
at what you do, like a really

00:19:12.870 --> 00:19:17.120
good day, the next day is
likely to be worse, just

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:18.080
statistically.

00:19:18.080 --> 00:19:20.000
So what's happening with
this flight instructor?

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.160
This is a very powerful and
important idea, that

00:19:22.160 --> 00:19:23.830
intuitively often, what's
happening with the flight

00:19:23.830 --> 00:19:24.440
instructor?

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:27.050
Of course if the guy does
awesome, he's going to do

00:19:27.050 --> 00:19:30.700
worse the next time, every
single time, practically,

00:19:30.700 --> 00:19:31.620
statistically.

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:35.200
So we can think about this,
regression to the mean.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:35.770
Here's a standard

00:19:35.770 --> 00:19:37.640
distribution, bell-shaped curve.

00:19:37.640 --> 00:19:39.560
Here's the mean of whatever
you do, how well you shoot

00:19:39.560 --> 00:19:41.785
baskets, how well you study for
a test, how well you wrote

00:19:41.785 --> 00:19:45.680
a paper, how well you helped a
friend who needed consoling.

00:19:45.680 --> 00:19:47.930
You pick your thing.

00:19:47.930 --> 00:19:49.610
Some days you do a medium job.

00:19:49.610 --> 00:19:50.540
You're average.

00:19:50.540 --> 00:19:54.150
Some days you really impress
yourself with how you did.

00:19:54.150 --> 00:19:57.270
And some days, you're pretty
shocked at what a miserable

00:19:57.270 --> 00:19:58.630
day you had.

00:19:58.630 --> 00:19:59.710
Does that makes sense?

00:19:59.710 --> 00:20:02.230
So if you had an awesome outing,
by average, the next

00:20:02.230 --> 00:20:06.220
outing is going to be less good,
regression to the mean.

00:20:08.790 --> 00:20:12.570
So one place that this has been
done over and over and

00:20:12.570 --> 00:20:14.290
over again, and somebody
help me out here.

00:20:14.290 --> 00:20:15.570
This could happen
in any sport.

00:20:15.570 --> 00:20:19.270
But especially in basketball,
people talk about a hot hand.

00:20:19.270 --> 00:20:21.050
So some of you are sports
enthusiasts.

00:20:21.050 --> 00:20:22.130
Probably some of you are not.

00:20:22.130 --> 00:20:25.250
So a sports enthusiast, will
you please help me describe

00:20:25.250 --> 00:20:30.410
what a hot hand is
in basketball?

00:20:30.410 --> 00:20:31.320
Help the rest of the class.

