But you just never hear about,
unless it unfortunately

00:31:44.370 --> 00:31:46.600
happens to somebody you know
personally, somebody slipping

00:31:46.600 --> 00:31:47.690
and dying in the bathtub.

00:31:47.690 --> 00:31:48.730
And it does happen.

00:31:48.730 --> 00:31:49.990
But you don't hear
about it much.

00:31:49.990 --> 00:31:50.720
It's not available to you.

00:31:50.720 --> 00:31:51.080
Yeah?

00:31:51.080 --> 00:31:53.972
AUDIENCE: We're most scared of
things that are foreign to us

00:31:53.972 --> 00:31:54.936
even if they are
less dangerous.

00:31:54.936 --> 00:31:58.068
Like we'd be more likely to
drink a clear fluid that was

00:31:58.068 --> 00:32:00.250
more dangerous than something
that looks scary.

00:32:00.250 --> 00:32:02.080
PROFESSOR: Part of it is, what
you're saying, there's a sense

00:32:02.080 --> 00:32:04.420
of foreignness to the terrorism
that we don't

00:32:04.420 --> 00:32:04.940
understand.

00:32:04.940 --> 00:32:06.440
Maybe there's a sense
of passivity.

00:32:06.440 --> 00:32:08.430
We feel like we could do
something about the bathroom.

00:32:08.430 --> 00:32:10.470
We can't do something about
an airplane being

00:32:10.470 --> 00:32:11.860
driven into a building.

00:32:11.860 --> 00:32:12.960
These things are complicated.

00:32:12.960 --> 00:32:17.450
But it's fascinating what people
think is scary versus

00:32:17.450 --> 00:32:19.750
what by any rational analysis,
is dangerous.

00:32:22.480 --> 00:32:26.640
Here's another kind of way that
people easily struggle

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:27.900
with numbers and thinking
about what's

00:32:27.900 --> 00:32:29.030
dangerous and not.

00:32:29.030 --> 00:32:31.100
So imagine you're a physician
and you're presented with this

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:31.380
information.

00:32:31.380 --> 00:32:34.090
And let's hypothesize
that it's true.

00:32:34.090 --> 00:32:35.230
Somebody comes in
with dizziness.

00:32:35.230 --> 00:32:37.390
And they say, I'm worried
about a brain tumor.

00:32:37.390 --> 00:32:38.700
They go to your neurologist.

00:32:38.700 --> 00:32:40.630
And the neurologist says well,
here we have some statistics

00:32:40.630 --> 00:32:43.360
over the last two years, whether
somebody turned out to

00:32:43.360 --> 00:32:46.300
have a brain tumor or not,
present or absent; and whether

00:32:46.300 --> 00:32:47.990
they were dizzy or not,
present or absent.

00:32:47.990 --> 00:32:52.320
So you can make a 2 x 2 cell,
about they had a tumor and

00:32:52.320 --> 00:32:56.040
they reported dizziness; they
reported dizziness, but it

00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:58.280
turns out they had the
tumor; and so on.

00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:00.330
So here's the question
for you.

00:33:00.330 --> 00:33:03.760
Is being dizzy something
to worry about in

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:05.480
terms of having a tumor?

00:33:05.480 --> 00:33:07.680
Should you be worried if you're
dizzy, that you might

00:33:07.680 --> 00:33:11.870
have a brain tumor,
by these numbers?

00:33:11.870 --> 00:33:14.020
So what do you think
most people think?

00:33:14.020 --> 00:33:16.900
You have to make
a quick answer.

00:33:16.900 --> 00:33:19.170
You're one of those doctors on
House, who's going to get

00:33:19.170 --> 00:33:21.320
berated in a moment.

00:33:21.320 --> 00:33:27.620
And you go, whoa, 160, bad.

00:33:27.620 --> 00:33:29.240
That's what a lot
of people feel.

00:33:29.240 --> 00:33:32.270
And by the way, there's a lot
of concern in medicine about

00:33:32.270 --> 00:33:36.140
how doctors convey risk to
patients, as patients pick

00:33:36.140 --> 00:33:37.740
what kind of treatment
they want.

00:33:37.740 --> 00:33:39.510
Because it's exactly what
we're talking about now.

00:33:39.510 --> 00:33:42.790
It's the exact way that you
convey to a patient, the risk

00:33:42.790 --> 00:33:45.540
they're facing or their family
member is facing among

00:33:45.540 --> 00:33:48.250
different treatment options.

00:33:48.250 --> 00:33:49.740
So is dizziness associated
with a brain tumor?

00:33:49.740 --> 00:33:53.820
And the answer is no, because
if you do the probabilities,

00:33:53.820 --> 00:33:56.170
so the probability of
a tumor is 4:1.

00:33:56.170 --> 00:34:00.680
So here's whether you have
the tumor, brain tumor.

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:03.450
And it's one out of four, and
it's one out of four.

00:34:03.450 --> 00:34:04.980
The odds are identical.

00:34:04.980 --> 00:34:07.460
But you're impressed by this
absolute, big number.

00:34:07.460 --> 00:34:12.440
Intuitively, almost everybody
is, almost all the time.

00:34:12.440 --> 00:34:13.739
Here's another one that's
a bit more subtle.

00:34:13.739 --> 00:34:15.489
It comes up all the time
in medical testing.

00:34:15.489 --> 00:34:18.150
It's come up in things like
discussions about how often we

00:34:18.150 --> 00:34:21.940
should test for, if you're a
male, for prostate cancer when

00:34:21.940 --> 00:34:26.060
you get older; if you're a
female, for breast cancer.

00:34:26.060 --> 00:34:28.340
So these kinds of things come
up all the time in decisions

00:34:28.340 --> 00:34:30.820
about should you get the tests
or not, and so on.

00:34:30.820 --> 00:34:33.130
So imagine now, a hypothetical
syndrome, is a serious

00:34:33.130 --> 00:34:35.889
condition that affects
one person in 1,000.

00:34:35.889 --> 00:34:38.760
Imagine also that the test to
diagnose the disease always

00:34:38.760 --> 00:34:41.170
indicates correctly that
a person who has it,

00:34:41.170 --> 00:34:42.899
actually has it.

00:34:42.899 --> 00:34:46.300
So if you actually have the
disorder and you get a yes,

00:34:46.300 --> 00:34:47.580
you will always be identified.

00:34:47.580 --> 00:34:49.630
So that's a good test
in that way.

00:34:49.630 --> 00:34:51.880
Finally, suppose the test
occasionally misidentifies a

00:34:51.880 --> 00:34:54.620
healthy individual as having
that disorder.

00:34:54.620 --> 00:34:56.370
So that's a false positive.

00:34:56.370 --> 00:34:58.340
The test is a false positive
at a rate of 5%.

00:34:58.340 --> 00:35:00.670
Meaning the test wrongly
indicates that the virus is

00:35:00.670 --> 00:35:02.640
present in 5% of cases
where the person does

00:35:02.640 --> 00:35:04.380
not have the virus.

00:35:04.380 --> 00:35:07.280
So if you have it, it's
always correct.

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:10.040
But 5% of healthy people will
be misidentified on the

00:35:10.040 --> 00:35:11.470
initial test.

00:35:11.470 --> 00:35:15.170
Choose a person at random,
administer the test, and the

00:35:15.170 --> 00:35:17.950
person tests positive
for that syndrome.

00:35:17.950 --> 00:35:21.630
What is the probability the
person really has that?

00:35:21.630 --> 00:35:24.760
This is the kind of medical
testing topic that goes on all

00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:26.050
the time, all the time.

00:35:30.840 --> 00:35:32.200
What do you think most people
are going to say?

00:35:35.984 --> 00:35:36.930
AUDIENCE: 95%.

00:35:36.930 --> 00:35:38.515
PROFESSOR: Yeah, 95% exactly.

00:35:38.515 --> 00:35:40.950
Because he said well, 5%
of the time it's wrong.

00:35:40.950 --> 00:35:42.840
But that ignores the base
rate of this order.

00:35:42.840 --> 00:35:46.110
Because if there's 1/1000,
then if the other 999 are

00:35:46.110 --> 00:35:51.140
tested, then you have
about 0.5 times 999.

00:35:51.140 --> 00:35:53.580
That means for every 51 who are
tested, only one has it.

00:35:53.580 --> 00:35:55.610
So the answer is
only about 2%.

00:35:55.610 --> 00:35:58.070
Because the odds, the prior
odds, that you have

00:35:58.070 --> 00:36:00.890
it are so, so low.

00:36:00.890 --> 00:36:03.470
So that comes into the
likelihood that it's an

00:36:03.470 --> 00:36:05.710
accurate test and the
false positive rate.

00:36:05.710 --> 00:36:07.840
So again, people's intuition
when they hear, their

00:36:07.840 --> 00:36:11.560
intuition is there's a 95%
probability that the person

00:36:11.560 --> 00:36:12.780
has the disorder.

00:36:12.780 --> 00:36:18.400
It's really only about 2%, given
the low known base rate.

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:20.650
And if all this is whizzing by
you a bit, I know I'm going

00:36:20.650 --> 00:36:22.050
through it pretty fast.

00:36:22.050 --> 00:36:23.730
But you can think in two ways.

00:36:23.730 --> 00:36:25.970
You can also think you're a
patient being told this.

00:36:25.970 --> 00:36:27.420
You're not going to get an
hour long lecture on

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:28.730
probabilities either.

00:36:28.730 --> 00:36:31.790
So how this is communicated to
physicians, for example in the

00:36:31.790 --> 00:36:36.120
medical area and families, is
a really big challenge.

00:36:36.120 --> 00:36:38.500
So we talked about two
heuristics, that people liked

00:36:38.500 --> 00:36:42.850
things to look random, that we
tend to go for what we often

00:36:42.850 --> 00:36:44.970
hear about and imagine that's
how frequent or dangerous

00:36:44.970 --> 00:36:48.920
something is, in a very
broad, intuitive way.

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:50.880
Anchoring and adjustment,
here's a fun one.

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:52.080
So here's the experiment
they did.

00:36:52.080 --> 00:36:54.926
They went to people, like in
courtyards around things that

00:36:54.926 --> 00:36:56.970
are around Stanford,
actually mostly.

00:36:56.970 --> 00:36:58.230
And they had them do
the following.

00:36:58.230 --> 00:37:02.850
They gave them either this
problem or this problem.

00:37:02.850 --> 00:37:05.230
And here's what happened.

00:37:05.230 --> 00:37:07.270
If they got this problem, and
they quickly had to guess the

00:37:07.270 --> 00:37:10.220
answer, they came up
with this many.

00:37:10.220 --> 00:37:12.130
This was their average estimate
and this was the

00:37:12.130 --> 00:37:13.090
average estimate.

00:37:13.090 --> 00:37:14.990
So the first thing we can agree
upon, regardless of the

00:37:14.990 --> 00:37:17.070
fact that everybody is
completely underestimating the

00:37:17.070 --> 00:37:18.530
actual answer--

00:37:18.530 --> 00:37:21.020
that's almost not the point--

00:37:21.020 --> 00:37:23.810
regardless of that, look
at this estimate.

00:37:23.810 --> 00:37:26.840
This rapid estimate is four
times greater than that.

00:37:26.840 --> 00:37:29.260
Why is that happening?

00:37:29.260 --> 00:37:30.890
You're only getting
one or the other.

00:37:30.890 --> 00:37:32.700
But why is that happening?

00:37:32.700 --> 00:37:35.960
This is the heuristic of
anchoring, how people come to

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:37.210
quick decisions.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.540
If we go, 8, that's a
pretty big number.

00:37:44.540 --> 00:37:47.000
8, we're talking some big
numbers here, right now.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:50.300
They don't even get that they're
going to get to here.

00:37:50.300 --> 00:37:51.890
They start with 1 and 2.

00:37:51.890 --> 00:37:54.340
They go, we're talking about
a pretty small thing.

00:37:54.340 --> 00:37:56.630
But I can't quite calculate it
out, because it's too hard to

00:37:56.630 --> 00:37:58.930
calculate it out
for most of us.

00:37:58.930 --> 00:38:01.110
This is going to be pretty small
by the time-- so they

00:38:01.110 --> 00:38:02.180
are already thinking small.

00:38:02.180 --> 00:38:04.860
They are already thinking big.

00:38:04.860 --> 00:38:08.600
So now you know why, when you
go negotiate for your salary

00:38:08.600 --> 00:38:11.490
somewhere in the future, if
you have any negotiating

00:38:11.490 --> 00:38:13.680
power, start with
a big number.

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:18.250
And the person who is
negotiating with you knows

00:38:18.250 --> 00:38:20.800
that too, and in fact is often
more practiced than you are.

00:38:20.800 --> 00:38:22.080
So here's a practical clue.

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:23.470
Start with a big number.

00:38:23.470 --> 00:38:24.960
Because that's the number where
people's minds are.

00:38:24.960 --> 00:38:26.520
And I'll show you several
more examples of how

00:38:26.520 --> 00:38:27.780
ridiculous this is.

00:38:27.780 --> 00:38:30.250
But when there's no true, exact
number that you can

00:38:30.250 --> 00:38:32.590
quickly come up with, what's
the fair salary for you to

00:38:32.590 --> 00:38:35.770
get, the first year out of MIT
in a job or something?

00:38:35.770 --> 00:38:39.100
First number out there,
has a lot of power.

00:38:39.100 --> 00:38:41.540
So here they made
it ridiculous.

00:38:41.540 --> 00:38:44.630
This anchoring, that my mind
start somewhere and I kind of

00:38:44.630 --> 00:38:45.810
stay in that neighborhood.

00:38:45.810 --> 00:38:47.750
I don't recalibrate myself.

00:38:47.750 --> 00:38:50.420
So they took a wheel of fortune,
a spinning wheel of

00:38:50.420 --> 00:38:52.100
fortune, with the numbers
1 to 100.

00:38:52.100 --> 00:38:53.590
It's clearly random.

00:38:53.590 --> 00:38:56.120
Can't make it more obviously
random than that.

00:38:56.120 --> 00:38:57.070
It stops somewhere.

00:38:57.070 --> 00:38:59.270
And they say, we want you to
estimate the number of African

00:38:59.270 --> 00:39:00.130
nations in the UN?

00:39:00.130 --> 00:39:01.320
And most people don't
really know.

00:39:01.320 --> 00:39:03.520
And there's some vague sense
that it's more than a couple.

00:39:03.520 --> 00:39:06.170
But who knows how big
it is exactly.

00:39:06.170 --> 00:39:08.210
So the number stops somewhere.

00:39:08.210 --> 00:39:10.400
And here's the kind of
thing that happens.

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:12.880
First you say, is it more or
less than the number it

00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:13.780
randomly stopped at?

00:39:13.780 --> 00:39:16.170
Let's pretend it
stopped at 65.

00:39:16.170 --> 00:39:20.190
Then average estimate was
45 African nations.

00:39:20.190 --> 00:39:22.110
Let's say it randomly
stopped at 10.

00:39:22.110 --> 00:39:26.170
Then the average estimate
was 25 nations.

00:39:26.170 --> 00:39:27.100
What's happening?

00:39:27.100 --> 00:39:28.390
Anchoring.

00:39:28.390 --> 00:39:29.890
You say well, it's
more than 10.

00:39:29.890 --> 00:39:33.280
But 10, I'm going to
go way up from 10.

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:34.820
Because that's way too low.

00:39:34.820 --> 00:39:36.250
And I'll split--

00:39:36.250 --> 00:39:38.980
going beyond 25 seems
hazardous.

00:39:38.980 --> 00:39:39.810
You start at 65.

00:39:39.810 --> 00:39:41.650
You go, whoa, that's
way too many.

00:39:41.650 --> 00:39:42.900
But you're anchored.

00:39:42.900 --> 00:39:45.310
And then you use don't
go down that much.

00:39:45.310 --> 00:39:47.870
So that first number, when you
don't really know what the

00:39:47.870 --> 00:39:50.970
right answer is, has an
incredible power over how far

00:39:50.970 --> 00:39:54.300
you range from that, for
your best estimate.

00:39:54.300 --> 00:39:55.450
Same idea.

00:39:55.450 --> 00:39:57.340
Is the Mississippi
River longer or

00:39:57.340 --> 00:39:58.610
shorter than 500 miles?

00:39:58.610 --> 00:40:00.120
So they're giving
you the anchor.

00:40:00.120 --> 00:40:01.910
How long is it actually
do you think?

00:40:01.910 --> 00:40:04.290
Or another person is asked, is
it longer or shorter than

00:40:04.290 --> 00:40:05.550
5,000 miles?

00:40:05.550 --> 00:40:06.520
There's the anchor.

00:40:06.520 --> 00:40:07.750
How long is it, do you think?

00:40:07.750 --> 00:40:09.440
And here's the estimates.

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:11.100
They're both underestimating.

00:40:11.100 --> 00:40:13.600
But they're moving towards
that number that was

00:40:13.600 --> 00:40:15.260
completely randomly thrown in.

00:40:15.260 --> 00:40:17.360
But it's not random
to the human mind.

00:40:17.360 --> 00:40:19.280
We don't know what the right
number is, but we're going to

00:40:19.280 --> 00:40:22.240
start in the neighborhood that
we first have any number

00:40:22.240 --> 00:40:24.470
presented to us.

00:40:24.470 --> 00:40:25.110
Framing.

00:40:25.110 --> 00:40:28.900
Framing is arguably, together
with availability, maybe the

00:40:28.900 --> 00:40:30.910
one that's the most interesting
in terms of how

00:40:30.910 --> 00:40:34.715
powerful it is and how often
people use it to convince you

00:40:34.715 --> 00:40:37.550
that their political position,
their corporate position,

00:40:37.550 --> 00:40:40.540
their anything, is
the way to go.

00:40:40.540 --> 00:40:43.300
And once you know framing,
you're empowered a bit to

00:40:43.300 --> 00:40:45.560
think about that, because you
hear arguments made to you

00:40:45.560 --> 00:40:47.460
about what to believe in
or what to support.

00:40:47.460 --> 00:40:48.970
So here comes the framing.

00:40:48.970 --> 00:40:50.955
Imagining the United States is
preparing for the outbreak of

00:40:50.955 --> 00:40:53.230
an unusual South American
disease, which is expected to

00:40:53.230 --> 00:40:54.870
kill 600 people.

00:40:54.870 --> 00:40:56.330
Two alternative programs
to combat the

00:40:56.330 --> 00:40:57.960
disease have been proposed.

00:40:57.960 --> 00:41:00.290
Assume that the exact scientific
estimate of the

00:41:00.290 --> 00:41:01.960
consequences of the programs
were as follows.

00:41:01.960 --> 00:41:04.580
If Program A is adopted, 200
people will be saved.

00:41:04.580 --> 00:41:06.690
If Program B is adopted,
there's a one-third

00:41:06.690 --> 00:41:09.300
probability the 600 people will
be saved and a two-thirds

00:41:09.300 --> 00:41:10.590
probability that no people
will be saved.

00:41:10.590 --> 00:41:12.640
Which program do you favor?

00:41:12.640 --> 00:41:14.590
So B is pretty complicated.

00:41:14.590 --> 00:41:17.200
But A is pretty simple,
200 people might be

00:41:17.200 --> 00:41:19.740
saved, will be saved.

00:41:19.740 --> 00:41:26.140
So here's the exact same
scenario by lives and deaths,

00:41:26.140 --> 00:41:30.600
given to a second group of
research participants.

00:41:30.600 --> 00:41:33.190
If Program A is adopted,
400 people will die.

00:41:33.190 --> 00:41:36.460
Do you see that if A is adopted,
200 people are saved,

00:41:36.460 --> 00:41:40.110
equals 400 people will die.

00:41:40.110 --> 00:41:40.680
It's the same thing.

00:41:40.680 --> 00:41:43.040
There's 600.

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:46.300
You're really saying
the same outcome.

00:41:46.300 --> 00:41:50.450
But that numerical identity
is treated by humans as

00:41:50.450 --> 00:41:53.370
incredibly different information
on which to base

00:41:53.370 --> 00:41:54.220
your decision.

00:41:54.220 --> 00:41:55.740
And here's what happens.

00:41:55.740 --> 00:41:58.000
If people are given this
scenario, which is explained

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:01.665
in terms of lives saved, 200
lives saved out of 600, 3/4 of

00:42:01.665 --> 00:42:02.875
the time they pick it.

00:42:02.875 --> 00:42:06.560
If people are given this
scenario, 3/4 of the time they

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:07.420
don't pick it.

00:42:07.420 --> 00:42:11.190
It's the exact same choice.

00:42:11.190 --> 00:42:16.220
But to be human, is to gravitate
towards something

00:42:16.220 --> 00:42:18.650
where you save lives
and avoid something

00:42:18.650 --> 00:42:20.460
where you lose lives.

00:42:20.460 --> 00:42:23.510
Even though numerically, it's
the exact same outcome.

00:42:23.510 --> 00:42:26.130
But people radically switch
which one they think is the

00:42:26.130 --> 00:42:27.670
correct one, by the
framing of it.

00:42:27.670 --> 00:42:29.610
By simply the way it's
described in

00:42:29.610 --> 00:42:31.880
this most simple sense.

00:42:31.880 --> 00:42:33.760
So does that makes sense?

00:42:33.760 --> 00:42:34.745
I mean it's very powerful.

00:42:34.745 --> 00:42:37.200
When people present to you
stuff, how do they present it?

00:42:37.200 --> 00:42:40.700
Lives saved, lives lost; jobs
made, jobs lost; whatever you

00:42:40.700 --> 00:42:43.690
want, money made, money lost.

00:42:43.690 --> 00:42:45.060
We don't treat them
as two bits of

00:42:45.060 --> 00:42:46.260
information that are equal.

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:47.280
We should.

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:51.390
That's the algorithm,
out of 600 people,

00:42:51.390 --> 00:42:53.430
200 people make it.

00:42:53.430 --> 00:42:55.680
But that's not how we
psychologically interpret it.

00:42:55.680 --> 00:42:57.940
We go tremendously
by, we're drawn--

00:42:57.940 --> 00:43:01.210
any answer that uses the word
"saves", is a positive thing.

00:43:01.210 --> 00:43:04.560
And we're averse from any answer
that talks about bad

00:43:04.560 --> 00:43:06.090
things, how many people
will die.

00:43:06.090 --> 00:43:07.730
Even though they're
identical in the

00:43:07.730 --> 00:43:09.310
consequence of life and death.

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:11.200
Is that clear?

00:43:11.200 --> 00:43:13.040
Very powerful.

00:43:13.040 --> 00:43:14.790
Here's another version of
it now, moving to money.

00:43:14.790 --> 00:43:16.480
And it gives you another
feeling of this.

00:43:16.480 --> 00:43:18.650
So you could think about
the top one.

00:43:18.650 --> 00:43:21.040
Would you rather have
a sure gain of $75.

00:43:21.040 --> 00:43:22.680
Somebody said, I'll give
you $75 right now.

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:25.690
Or you can have a lottery where
you have a 75% chance of

00:43:25.690 --> 00:43:29.430
winning $100, so that's even
more, or a 25% chance of

00:43:29.430 --> 00:43:30.680
winning nothing at all.

00:43:33.970 --> 00:43:35.630
Another group of people
get this question.

00:43:35.630 --> 00:43:37.540
We're going to take
from you $75.

00:43:37.540 --> 00:43:40.781
It's a rough experiment
to sign up for.

00:43:40.781 --> 00:43:44.220
Or you're going to be in a
lottery with a 75% chance of

00:43:44.220 --> 00:43:48.060
losing $100, which is even a
worse loss, and 25% chance of

00:43:48.060 --> 00:43:49.460
losing nothing at all.

00:43:49.460 --> 00:43:52.260
So these are meant to be kind
of symmetric stories.

00:43:52.260 --> 00:43:56.370
But one is expressed all in
terms of gain and one all in

00:43:56.370 --> 00:43:57.590
terms of losses.

00:43:57.590 --> 00:44:02.380
And when people are thinking
about gains,

00:44:02.380 --> 00:44:03.890
they're risk averse.

00:44:03.890 --> 00:44:06.590
I'm not going to give up
what's in my hands.

00:44:06.590 --> 00:44:10.520
So 84% of the time,
they take that.

00:44:10.520 --> 00:44:13.110
Even though this is sort of
formally similar because it's

00:44:13.110 --> 00:44:17.350
a loss, now when it's losses,
people are risk taking.

00:44:17.350 --> 00:44:19.470
Humans are very asymmetric.

00:44:19.470 --> 00:44:21.750
If things are expressed in
gains, we're risk averse.

00:44:21.750 --> 00:44:22.970
Let's do the safe thing.

00:44:22.970 --> 00:44:25.740
I'm going to hang on to what's
already in my grasp.

00:44:25.740 --> 00:44:28.730
If it's in terms of loss, it's
like, let's bet the house,

00:44:28.730 --> 00:44:30.670
let's do any crazy,
wild thing.

00:44:30.670 --> 00:44:33.910
Because losses are so bad
that I'll take any

00:44:33.910 --> 00:44:35.900
chance to avoid a loss.

00:44:35.900 --> 00:44:38.980
Even though rationally, the
choices should be about the

00:44:38.980 --> 00:44:42.460
same, if we were machines
making choices.

00:44:42.460 --> 00:44:44.060
Very big difference.

00:44:44.060 --> 00:44:45.820
I mean when I first
heard about these

00:44:45.820 --> 00:44:46.730
things, I was stunned.

00:44:46.730 --> 00:44:48.650
Because it's huge.

00:44:48.650 --> 00:44:51.120
Everything that we vote for,
everything that we support,

00:44:51.120 --> 00:44:54.730
every decision we make about
careers, and policies that we

00:44:54.730 --> 00:44:57.960
are for or against, are always
being expressed to us in a

00:44:57.960 --> 00:44:59.350
framework like this.

00:44:59.350 --> 00:45:01.920
Things that we can gain or lose
in our own lives, in the

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:03.870
world, in societies.

00:45:03.870 --> 00:45:07.790
And you spin around so easily
by how they're framed.

00:45:07.790 --> 00:45:08.980
Although now you
know something.

00:45:08.980 --> 00:45:10.230
And you can think about them.

00:45:12.570 --> 00:45:14.830
Here's just two odds and ends
things, that I thought were

00:45:14.830 --> 00:45:17.470
kind of fun.

00:45:17.470 --> 00:45:19.800
Other things that people find
kind of challenging to think

00:45:19.800 --> 00:45:22.320
their way through, just because
of the way our minds

00:45:22.320 --> 00:45:22.920
are constructed.

00:45:22.920 --> 00:45:24.390
So here's a problem.

00:45:24.390 --> 00:45:27.480
Jack is looking at Anne, but
Anne is looking at George.

00:45:27.480 --> 00:45:31.260
Jack is married, but
George is not.

00:45:31.260 --> 00:45:32.750
Here's your problem
to think about.

00:45:32.750 --> 00:45:39.040
Is a married person looking at
an unmarried person, yes, no,

00:45:39.040 --> 00:45:40.290
or cannot be determined?

00:45:46.970 --> 00:45:48.560
The only reason I know the
answers to these is because I

00:45:48.560 --> 00:45:49.830
have the answers to these.

00:45:49.830 --> 00:45:52.480
The first time I see these,
I'm like, oh no.

00:45:52.480 --> 00:45:57.500
So just for fun.

00:45:57.500 --> 00:45:59.970
You can go by intuition and
maybe you worked it out or you

00:45:59.970 --> 00:46:01.170
looked ahead.

00:46:01.170 --> 00:46:05.420
How many people who haven't
looked ahead, say yes?

00:46:05.420 --> 00:46:07.360
OK, there's some hands, 10.

00:46:07.360 --> 00:46:09.360
How many say no?

00:46:09.360 --> 00:46:09.580
Nobody.

00:46:09.580 --> 00:46:11.750
How many say, cannot
be determined?

00:46:11.750 --> 00:46:14.680
The answer is, that's good.

00:46:14.680 --> 00:46:18.046
Most answer, 80% say cannot
be determined.

00:46:18.046 --> 00:46:20.800
But the answer is this.

00:46:20.800 --> 00:46:21.390
Think about this.

00:46:21.390 --> 00:46:22.160
The answer is yes.

00:46:22.160 --> 00:46:23.340
And here's why.

00:46:23.340 --> 00:46:24.510
We don't know Anne's
marital status.

00:46:24.510 --> 00:46:25.200
The other two are given.

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:27.230
So we have to figure out
Anne's situation.

00:46:27.230 --> 00:46:28.860
Let's say she's married.

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:31.150
Then she's looking at
unmarried George.

00:46:31.150 --> 00:46:31.960
Let's say she's not married.

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:33.070
Then Jack is looking
at unmarried Anne.

00:46:33.070 --> 00:46:34.420
Is that OK?

00:46:34.420 --> 00:46:36.560
This is what people in logic,
call fully disjunctive

00:46:36.560 --> 00:46:40.610
reasoning, where if you work
your way through the

00:46:40.610 --> 00:46:43.140
possibilities, you see
it has to work out.

00:46:43.140 --> 00:46:46.930
But that's not our intuitions.

00:46:46.930 --> 00:46:51.250
I mean you're a very
smart group.

00:46:51.250 --> 00:46:54.620
So if it's hard for you, imagine
the rest of the world

00:46:54.620 --> 00:46:57.250
is not as suspicious about how
to figure their problems out.

00:46:57.250 --> 00:47:00.010
So it's just fantastically
interesting how the human mind

00:47:00.010 --> 00:47:01.410
is brilliant at some things.

00:47:01.410 --> 00:47:05.850
And for other things, it could
solve, it could solve,

00:47:05.850 --> 00:47:07.970
intuitively, it's not often
going to happen.

00:47:07.970 --> 00:47:10.450
We go by these shortcuts where
either we don't get the answer

00:47:10.450 --> 00:47:12.690
at all or we come up with a
completely wrong one, because

00:47:12.690 --> 00:47:15.450
of availability or framing.

00:47:15.450 --> 00:47:15.970
Here's a quick one.

00:47:15.970 --> 00:47:17.100
You'll get this fast.

00:47:17.100 --> 00:47:17.740
It's fun.

00:47:17.740 --> 00:47:20.810
A ball and a bat cost
$1.10 in total.

00:47:20.810 --> 00:47:22.100
The bat cost a dollar
more than the ball.

00:47:22.100 --> 00:47:25.330
How much did the ball cost?

00:47:25.330 --> 00:47:26.780
All right, you guys are now,
you're very suspicious.

00:47:26.780 --> 00:47:28.150
You're thinking it through.

00:47:28.150 --> 00:47:30.330
Most people love $0.10.

00:47:30.330 --> 00:47:33.330
But you can tell that's
not going to work?

00:47:33.330 --> 00:47:35.520
Because then the bat would have
to cost $1.10 and the

00:47:35.520 --> 00:47:38.700
total would be $1.20.

00:47:38.700 --> 00:47:44.230
But a lot you were pulled to,
most of us to, having a $1.10,

00:47:44.230 --> 00:47:45.490
because we don't quite
think it through.

00:47:45.490 --> 00:47:46.030
There's $1.00.

00:47:46.030 --> 00:47:47.060
There's $0.10.

00:47:47.060 --> 00:47:49.400
And we do these shortcuts, these
heuristics, instead of

00:47:49.400 --> 00:47:52.250
logically working
our way through.

00:47:52.250 --> 00:47:54.390
One more example of this
kind of thing.

00:47:54.390 --> 00:47:55.950
Because now we're going
to add one more

00:47:55.950 --> 00:47:56.940
element just for this.

00:47:56.940 --> 00:47:58.950
Imagine that the US Department
of Transportation has found

00:47:58.950 --> 00:48:00.860
that a particular German car
is eight times more likely

00:48:00.860 --> 00:48:03.370
than a typical family car to
kill occupants of another car

00:48:03.370 --> 00:48:04.500
in a crash.

00:48:04.500 --> 00:48:06.260
The federal government is
considering restricting sale

00:48:06.260 --> 00:48:07.230
and use of this German car.

00:48:07.230 --> 00:48:09.090
Do you think sales of the German
car should be banned in

00:48:09.090 --> 00:48:12.300
the US or do you think the
German car should be banned

00:48:12.300 --> 00:48:13.670
from being driven on
the US streets?

00:48:13.670 --> 00:48:18.860
So here's one, given in this
study to US participants.

00:48:18.860 --> 00:48:20.600
Or to do exactly the same
thing, but it's

00:48:20.600 --> 00:48:21.690
not a German car.

00:48:21.690 --> 00:48:22.940
It's a Ford Explorer.

00:48:25.960 --> 00:48:29.600
So American participants, if
it's a German car, 73%, get

00:48:29.600 --> 00:48:31.610
that car off the road.

00:48:31.610 --> 00:48:35.230
If it's a Ford Explorer,
sorry.

00:48:35.230 --> 00:48:37.300
If a German car, off the
streets, you get 73%, If it's

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:40.110
the American car, and Germany
is making the decision, only

00:48:40.110 --> 00:48:43.560
40% of the people think that
Germany should do that.

00:48:43.560 --> 00:48:45.400
Now, that's not purely logic.

00:48:45.400 --> 00:48:47.280
What is that?

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:48.130
That's bias, right?

00:48:48.130 --> 00:48:51.140
That's like, yeah, on my
streets, we don't want these

00:48:51.140 --> 00:48:53.720
threatening machines
from overseas.

00:48:53.720 --> 00:48:55.730
Germany, we've got to keep
that economy going.

00:48:55.730 --> 00:48:58.310
Those Ford workers are really
doing a good job.

00:48:58.310 --> 00:49:02.340
So of course most decisions
aren't hyperrational in the

00:49:02.340 --> 00:49:03.860
way we've been talking about,
unknown people.

00:49:03.860 --> 00:49:06.800
Of course they involve things
in the world that we already

00:49:06.800 --> 00:49:07.650
have feelings about.

00:49:07.650 --> 00:49:10.500
So you add that in and you can
see that making a truly

00:49:10.500 --> 00:49:13.690
logical judgment is shockingly
hard, if anything is a little

00:49:13.690 --> 00:49:15.750
complicated.

00:49:15.750 --> 00:49:19.370
So let me turn for the last
little bit to what we think of

00:49:19.370 --> 00:49:22.260
as some of the core parts of
the brain for higher level

00:49:22.260 --> 00:49:25.770
thought, the struggle we have
between the best we have in

00:49:25.770 --> 00:49:28.730
our mind and the traps
we can fall into.

00:49:28.730 --> 00:49:32.650
And when we talk about that,
we tend to focus on sort of

00:49:32.650 --> 00:49:33.820
three areas of the
frontal lobe.

00:49:33.820 --> 00:49:36.380
So let me just remind
you of this.

00:49:36.380 --> 00:49:39.370
So here's the frontal lobes.

00:49:39.370 --> 00:49:41.210
And you could think of the
frontal lobe I think as the

00:49:41.210 --> 00:49:43.210
business end of the brain.

00:49:43.210 --> 00:49:45.510
Here comes visual information
coming in, auditory

00:49:45.510 --> 00:49:47.800
information coming in,
touch coming in.

00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:51.760
Somewhere back here,
would be taste.

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:54.750
So that's getting stuck in and
figuring out what's out there.

00:49:54.750 --> 00:49:57.350
So the front half is the
business end of the brain,

00:49:57.350 --> 00:49:58.360
acting upon the world.

00:49:58.360 --> 00:50:01.020
Moving your hands, moving your
body, making decisions about

00:50:01.020 --> 00:50:02.580
what you do.

00:50:02.580 --> 00:50:06.100
Motor cortex, premotor cortex,
a guy's motor cortex.

00:50:06.100 --> 00:50:08.340
This so-called lateral
prefrontal cortex, that's

00:50:08.340 --> 00:50:10.030
higher levels of thought.

00:50:10.030 --> 00:50:12.900
And this bottom part of
ventromedial or orbitofrontal

00:50:12.900 --> 00:50:15.920
cortex, that we talked about
with Phineas Gage.

00:50:15.920 --> 00:50:20.260
So Oliver Sacks, in Chapter 13,
talks about one example of

00:50:20.260 --> 00:50:25.330
a woman who has a large tumor
in this ventromedial area.

00:50:25.330 --> 00:50:29.610
So sometimes I think there's a
Roman philosopher who said

00:50:29.610 --> 00:50:33.130
that life is composed of desires
and decisions, desires

00:50:33.130 --> 00:50:34.070
and decisions.

00:50:34.070 --> 00:50:36.400
So this part of the brain is
involved in desires and this

00:50:36.400 --> 00:50:37.210
part in decisions.

00:50:37.210 --> 00:50:39.210
And I'll show that,
roughly speaking.

00:50:39.210 --> 00:50:42.620
So here's a woman who is a
former research chemist.

00:50:42.620 --> 00:50:44.830
And she has a rapid personality
change, becoming

00:50:44.830 --> 00:50:47.450
facetious, impulsive,
superficial.

00:50:47.450 --> 00:50:49.430
And she a cerebral
tumor in this

00:50:49.430 --> 00:50:51.540
ventromedial part of the brain.

00:50:51.540 --> 00:50:53.540
When I see her, she's full
of quips and cracks,

00:50:53.540 --> 00:50:55.020
often clever and funny.

00:50:55.020 --> 00:50:57.425
Yes, father, she says to me on
one occasion; yes, sister, on

00:50:57.425 --> 00:50:59.230
another; yes, doctor,
on a third.

00:50:59.230 --> 00:50:59.960
What am I?

00:50:59.960 --> 00:51:01.620
And then she make some jokes.

00:51:01.620 --> 00:51:03.260
So she's constantly joking.

00:51:03.260 --> 00:51:08.030
And she says, everything
means nothing.

00:51:08.030 --> 00:51:10.090
Nothing at all, she says with
a bright smile and a tone of

00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:13.020
one who makes a joke, wins an
argument, or wins at poker.

00:51:13.020 --> 00:51:17.090
So she just finds that sort of
there are facts of the world,

00:51:17.090 --> 00:51:20.010
but they just don't feel like
they mean anything.

00:51:20.010 --> 00:51:22.460
Because a tumor is influencing
a part of the brain that we

00:51:22.460 --> 00:51:26.450
understand to organize the
relationship between thoughts

00:51:26.450 --> 00:51:28.450
and feelings, between thoughts
and feelings.

00:51:28.450 --> 00:51:31.150
And that's a huge way about
how we go about the world,

00:51:31.150 --> 00:51:32.650
what we think, what we feel.

00:51:32.650 --> 00:51:34.360
We've put it into a formula
of some sense.

00:51:34.360 --> 00:51:36.590
And that's how we act upon the
world, whether we help

00:51:36.590 --> 00:51:38.390
somebody, or don't help
somebody, like somebody, or

00:51:38.390 --> 00:51:39.350
don't like somebody.

00:51:39.350 --> 00:51:40.860
All those sorts of things.

00:51:40.860 --> 00:51:47.690
So when we think about behavior,
we normally think of

00:51:47.690 --> 00:51:49.830
the challenge of getting
it going.

00:51:49.830 --> 00:51:52.020
You get in your car and you
turn on and you accelerate

00:51:52.020 --> 00:51:53.190
from 0 to 60.

00:51:53.190 --> 00:51:55.680
But a really interesting thing
about the human brain is that

00:51:55.680 --> 00:51:59.030
we have lots of habits, things
we acquire about how to deal

00:51:59.030 --> 00:51:59.640
with the world.

00:51:59.640 --> 00:52:03.540
So just as big a problem for
our brains is stopping the

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:07.490
course of action that's
no longer relevant.

00:52:07.490 --> 00:52:10.520
So the frontal cortex both has
the job of initiating things,

00:52:10.520 --> 00:52:11.870
but also stopping things.

00:52:11.870 --> 00:52:14.280
And you can see it in a couple
of ways, I'll show you.

00:52:14.280 --> 00:52:15.860
So here's an example
of a patient with a

00:52:15.860 --> 00:52:17.880
frontal lobe injury.

00:52:17.880 --> 00:52:21.090
They're drawn this scratchily,
by a physician.

00:52:21.090 --> 00:52:22.480
And here's their exact copy.

00:52:22.480 --> 00:52:24.950
Do you see they can't stop?

00:52:24.950 --> 00:52:26.590
Here's again the model,

00:52:26.590 --> 00:52:27.750
scratched out by the physician.

00:52:27.750 --> 00:52:28.460
Look at the patient.

00:52:28.460 --> 00:52:30.360
The patient can't stop.

00:52:30.360 --> 00:52:32.000
So the problem's not starting.

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:35.060
The problem is stopping the
mental operation once it's

00:52:35.060 --> 00:52:36.550
going and repeating.

00:52:36.550 --> 00:52:39.250
And it's hard to put on
the mental breaks.

00:52:39.250 --> 00:52:42.860
Here's an example of a
behavioral test of that kind.

00:52:42.860 --> 00:52:45.650
And I remember this, when I was
testing patients in E17

00:52:45.650 --> 00:52:48.170
and E18 here, I did
this a fair bit.

00:52:48.170 --> 00:52:50.770
It's called the Wisconsin
Card Sorting Test.

00:52:50.770 --> 00:52:54.330
And what happens is, you put
on four cards like these.

00:52:54.330 --> 00:52:54.930
These are the key cards.

00:52:54.930 --> 00:52:56.310
It's very mysterious when
you give the test.

00:52:56.310 --> 00:52:58.400
You just put them down.

00:52:58.400 --> 00:53:00.860
And you have a pile of
cards over here.

00:53:00.860 --> 00:53:03.410
And you tell the person, your
job is to pick a card from

00:53:03.410 --> 00:53:07.090
this pile and put it below
one of these cards.

00:53:07.090 --> 00:53:10.370
And I'll tell you if you're
right or wrong.

00:53:10.370 --> 00:53:12.120
And then use that information
to know where to

00:53:12.120 --> 00:53:13.840
put the next card.

00:53:13.840 --> 00:53:15.800
So imagine you are doing this
experiment, and if you're

00:53:15.800 --> 00:53:17.440
color blind, there's
an extra issue.

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:17.960
I'll just warn you.

00:53:17.960 --> 00:53:20.610
But you get this first card.

00:53:20.610 --> 00:53:21.960
Where would you put it below?

00:53:21.960 --> 00:53:23.516
Where could you put it below?

00:53:23.516 --> 00:53:25.500
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:25.500 --> 00:53:26.140
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:53:26.140 --> 00:53:27.090
That has an equal number.

00:53:27.090 --> 00:53:27.840
That's one possibility.

00:53:27.840 --> 00:53:30.430
What's another possibility, as
the rule by which you might

00:53:30.430 --> 00:53:31.510
sort the card?

00:53:31.510 --> 00:53:31.980
AUDIENCE: Color.

00:53:31.980 --> 00:53:32.510
PROFESSOR: Color.

00:53:32.510 --> 00:53:33.110
Yeah, that's green.

00:53:33.110 --> 00:53:33.650
That goes with that.

00:53:33.650 --> 00:53:35.340
What's another possibility
that you can see?

00:53:35.340 --> 00:53:35.635
Shape.

00:53:35.635 --> 00:53:37.320
You can say that's a plus sign,
that's a plus sign.

00:53:37.320 --> 00:53:38.770
They all seem reasonable.

00:53:38.770 --> 00:53:40.915
So people usually pick
one of those three.

00:53:40.915 --> 00:53:44.510
And if they happen to pick the
one that I as a tester know

00:53:44.510 --> 00:53:47.070
from my instruction sheet,
it's my job to reinforce.

00:53:47.070 --> 00:53:49.770
Let's pretend it starts
with color.

00:53:49.770 --> 00:53:51.920
If they do this, I go wrong.

00:53:51.920 --> 00:53:54.020
I go, hmm.

00:53:54.020 --> 00:53:55.930
And they pick another card and
they try something else.

00:53:55.930 --> 00:53:58.160
They pick another card and
they try something else.

00:53:58.160 --> 00:54:00.200
And after three or four
cards, people pretty

00:54:00.200 --> 00:54:02.830
much get the color.

00:54:02.830 --> 00:54:04.240
And then you go get
another card out.

00:54:04.240 --> 00:54:07.840
You go right, right, right,
right right, wrong.

00:54:07.840 --> 00:54:10.980
And when I did this, I was
approximately your age.

00:54:10.980 --> 00:54:12.430
And most of the patients
I tested were older.

00:54:12.430 --> 00:54:15.180
And they go like, sonny, look
back on your score sheet

00:54:15.180 --> 00:54:16.140
because it's correct.

00:54:16.140 --> 00:54:17.580
And I go no ma'am, no sir.

00:54:17.580 --> 00:54:18.170
I'm sorry about that.

00:54:18.170 --> 00:54:19.520
But it's wrong.

00:54:19.520 --> 00:54:22.050
Because what you do is after
10 consecutive correct

00:54:22.050 --> 00:54:26.910
responses, you switch the rule
from color to shape.

00:54:26.910 --> 00:54:29.510
After 10 correct shape,
you switch to number.

00:54:29.510 --> 00:54:30.360
And then you do that again.

00:54:30.360 --> 00:54:32.400
So you switch the
rule after 10.

00:54:32.400 --> 00:54:35.500
So it's a test of mental
flexibility, in a fairly

00:54:35.500 --> 00:54:36.090
simple way.

00:54:36.090 --> 00:54:37.300
Does that make sense?

00:54:37.300 --> 00:54:39.040
They have to figure out
what the answer is.

00:54:39.040 --> 00:54:39.960
Then they're zooming along.

00:54:39.960 --> 00:54:41.806
And you go, no stop.

00:54:41.806 --> 00:54:44.160
And you have to come up
with the next answer.

00:54:44.160 --> 00:54:47.790
So here's what happens for
patients with frontal lobe

00:54:47.790 --> 00:54:50.490
lesions, they make a huge
amount of what's called

00:54:50.490 --> 00:54:52.260
perseverative errors.

00:54:52.260 --> 00:54:55.550
So this is now the intellectual
analog of the too

00:54:55.550 --> 00:54:57.320
many squiggles.

00:54:57.320 --> 00:55:01.870
Once they get that first rule,
they can't stop that rule.

00:55:01.870 --> 00:55:04.150
So they go color, color,
color, color, color.

00:55:04.150 --> 00:55:05.740
They get about 10.

00:55:05.740 --> 00:55:06.640
So you switch.

00:55:06.640 --> 00:55:07.730
And they just keep doing it.

00:55:07.730 --> 00:55:11.150
You go no, wrong, wrong,
wrong, wrong, wrong.

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:14.310
But they can't stop the rule
that worked in the first

00:55:14.310 --> 00:55:17.950
place, without the prefrontal
cortex being intact.

00:55:17.950 --> 00:55:20.800
So our mental flexibility seems
to depend tremendously

00:55:20.800 --> 00:55:22.470
on prefrontal cortex.

00:55:22.470 --> 00:55:24.510
And you can do the same kind of
thing in imaging, just to

00:55:24.510 --> 00:55:25.740
make sure it's not just
a patient thing.

00:55:25.740 --> 00:55:29.090
And again, when you have to do
this very same kind of task,

00:55:29.090 --> 00:55:32.410
typical people activate
prefrontal cortex to do the

00:55:32.410 --> 00:55:36.490
mental manipulation of the
simple problem solving task.

00:55:36.490 --> 00:55:38.640
So we talked about
perserveration and its hard to

00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:41.000
stop and mental flexibility.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:43.240
With ventromedial lesions, you
get some weird things.

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:44.960
You get what they call
utilization behaviors.

00:55:44.960 --> 00:55:47.720
So again, we're having this
idea what's the good thing

00:55:47.720 --> 00:55:49.820
about having very
powerful habits?

00:55:53.400 --> 00:55:55.980
Is it very good to have very
powerful habits, and we use a

00:55:55.980 --> 00:55:59.470
different word for this,
when you read?

00:55:59.470 --> 00:55:59.930
Yeah.

00:55:59.930 --> 00:56:00.820
Because that's how you're
a fast reader.

00:56:00.820 --> 00:56:02.990
You know how to read
words really fast.

00:56:02.990 --> 00:56:07.126
Is it good to have very powerful
habits when you walk?

00:56:07.126 --> 00:56:07.710
Yeah.

00:56:07.710 --> 00:56:10.050
You don't want to go like, OK,
I'm moving the leg now.

00:56:10.050 --> 00:56:10.860
Everybody get ready.

00:56:10.860 --> 00:56:11.780
We're moving the other leg.

00:56:11.780 --> 00:56:13.540
Because you could never get
out of the room very

00:56:13.540 --> 00:56:14.340
efficiently.

00:56:14.340 --> 00:56:17.090
So for many, many things, having
very powerful habits

00:56:17.090 --> 00:56:17.840
are very strong.

00:56:17.840 --> 00:56:21.650
But for other things, they're
not as good and you have to

00:56:21.650 --> 00:56:22.270
put the brakes on.

00:56:22.270 --> 00:56:24.480
So Lhermitte described patients
with ventromedial

00:56:24.480 --> 00:56:27.150
lesions who came in,
saw in his office.

00:56:27.150 --> 00:56:28.300
This was not a set-up
experiment.

00:56:28.300 --> 00:56:29.440
He didn't expect this.

00:56:29.440 --> 00:56:30.694
There was a hammer, a
nail, and a picture.

00:56:30.694 --> 00:56:32.550
And the patient just
goes over, up.

00:56:32.550 --> 00:56:34.770
And you could imagine, if you
go into the doctor's office

00:56:34.770 --> 00:56:37.710
and you see a hammer, a nail,
and a picture, would you go

00:56:37.710 --> 00:56:39.630
over and put up the picture?

00:56:39.630 --> 00:56:40.740
No.

00:56:40.740 --> 00:56:42.610
I mean you know that's what
you do with that stuff.

00:56:42.610 --> 00:56:44.140
You know that's what's
going on.

00:56:44.140 --> 00:56:45.730
But you go, that's not my place
to do it, even though

00:56:45.730 --> 00:56:46.750
it's attempted to do it.

00:56:46.750 --> 00:56:48.450
The patient could not help
himself but go do that,

00:56:48.450 --> 00:56:49.740
literally go do that.

00:56:49.740 --> 00:56:52.090
The most dramatic example was,
the patient walks in and sees

00:56:52.090 --> 00:56:54.080
a hypodermic needle, pulls down
his pants, and injects

00:56:54.080 --> 00:56:56.810
himself in the derriere.

00:56:56.810 --> 00:56:59.740
So again, he knew that
was going to happen.

00:56:59.740 --> 00:57:01.060
He knew that's the habit.

00:57:01.060 --> 00:57:02.950
But you wouldn't go into a
doctor's office and start

00:57:02.950 --> 00:57:05.160
using their stuff and
perform on yourself.

00:57:05.160 --> 00:57:05.680
You understand.

00:57:05.680 --> 00:57:08.330
The habits are completely
running the show.

00:57:08.330 --> 00:57:11.010
And any kind of frontal cortical
control of those

00:57:11.010 --> 00:57:14.030
habits has been eliminated
in these patients.

00:57:14.030 --> 00:57:15.115
And here's a couple
more things that

00:57:15.115 --> 00:57:16.920
are along that line.

00:57:16.920 --> 00:57:20.550
So I need a volunteer, in your
seats, to try something with

00:57:20.550 --> 00:57:21.800
me for a minute.

00:57:23.730 --> 00:57:25.080
It's not bad.

00:57:25.080 --> 00:57:27.420
I think I've traumatized
you in these examples.

00:57:27.420 --> 00:57:29.250
OK, thank you.

00:57:29.250 --> 00:57:30.970
If you had to answer this
question, and there's no

00:57:30.970 --> 00:57:31.530
correct answer.

00:57:31.530 --> 00:57:33.110
But let's just talk about
how you might do it.

00:57:33.110 --> 00:57:35.577
How long is a man's
spine, on average?

00:57:35.577 --> 00:57:37.020
AUDIENCE: About two feet?

00:57:37.020 --> 00:57:38.220
PROFESSOR: And how did you
kind of come to that?

00:57:38.220 --> 00:57:39.548
And that might be
right or not.

00:57:39.548 --> 00:57:42.416
AUDIENCE: My back is roughly
two feet long.

00:57:42.416 --> 00:57:45.290
My spine is--

00:57:45.290 --> 00:57:45.660
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:57:45.660 --> 00:57:47.280
It's got to be less
seven feet.

00:57:47.280 --> 00:57:49.750
Because that's like the tallest
basketball players.

00:57:49.750 --> 00:57:51.950
On average, it's got to be
more than a couple feet.

00:57:51.950 --> 00:57:52.890
Something in that range.

00:57:52.890 --> 00:57:54.680
OK, you just guessed
which it was.

00:57:54.680 --> 00:57:56.860
Or how fast does a horse
in a race gallop?

00:57:56.860 --> 00:57:59.720
Or what's the largest object
normally found in the house?

00:57:59.720 --> 00:58:01.854
What do you think
that might be?

00:58:01.854 --> 00:58:02.730
AUDIENCE: Fridge?

00:58:02.730 --> 00:58:03.500
PROFESSOR: Help me out here.

00:58:03.500 --> 00:58:03.830
AUDIENCE: A refrigerator.

00:58:03.830 --> 00:58:04.970
PROFESSOR: A refrigerator
is a good one.

00:58:04.970 --> 00:58:06.052
Anybody else?

00:58:06.052 --> 00:58:07.290
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:07.290 --> 00:58:08.110
PROFESSOR: All those are good.

00:58:08.110 --> 00:58:09.600
Is toaster a good answer?

00:58:09.600 --> 00:58:11.310
No.

00:58:11.310 --> 00:58:11.880
One more person.

00:58:11.880 --> 00:58:12.650
Who's going to help
me out here?

00:58:12.650 --> 00:58:13.900
One more example.

00:58:21.160 --> 00:58:21.780
Come on.

00:58:21.780 --> 00:58:22.100
One more example.

00:58:22.100 --> 00:58:22.340
It's easy.

00:58:22.340 --> 00:58:23.580
OK, thank you, Rich.

00:58:23.580 --> 00:58:26.090
How many camels are there
in the Netherlands?

00:58:26.090 --> 00:58:27.310
Now, nobody knows.

00:58:27.310 --> 00:58:30.010
But tell me a thought process
roughly, so you would come up

00:58:30.010 --> 00:58:31.063
with an estimate.

00:58:31.063 --> 00:58:32.050
AUDIENCE: 100.

00:58:32.050 --> 00:58:32.600
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:58:32.600 --> 00:58:34.830
Because are you going to figure
there's a lot in the

00:58:34.830 --> 00:58:35.785
Netherlands?

00:58:35.785 --> 00:58:36.140
No.

00:58:36.140 --> 00:58:37.850
Because there's no
desert, right?

00:58:37.850 --> 00:58:40.410
Where might you find a few?

00:58:40.410 --> 00:58:42.610
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:42.610 --> 00:58:43.976
PROFESSOR: On a ranch.

00:58:43.976 --> 00:58:46.660
I haven't been to Amsterdam
for a while, so perhaps

00:58:46.660 --> 00:58:50.395
there's a few loping around
in the canals.

00:58:50.395 --> 00:58:54.130
And some zoo, some kids' petting
thing, who knows?

00:58:54.130 --> 00:58:56.030
So, yeah, 100 sounds
good to me.

00:58:56.030 --> 00:58:58.860
But frontal patients will
give really bad answers,

00:58:58.860 --> 00:59:00.620
thousands or zero.

00:59:00.620 --> 00:59:02.560
Or 12 feet for a spinal cord.

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:03.600
Or just something that
you go like, where

00:59:03.600 --> 00:59:05.250
did you come up that?

00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:06.760
You can do the Price Is
Right game with them.

00:59:06.760 --> 00:59:08.920
They'll come up with more
ridiculous answers.

00:59:08.920 --> 00:59:09.950
Here's just a graph.

00:59:09.950 --> 00:59:12.770
These are bad answers for how
expensive something is, just

00:59:12.770 --> 00:59:14.280
unreasonable answers
within these sort

00:59:14.280 --> 00:59:15.760
of open-ended questions.

00:59:15.760 --> 00:59:18.330
Or you can do more
formal problems.

00:59:18.330 --> 00:59:20.640
The kind of problem
where you're given

00:59:20.640 --> 00:59:21.380
a puzzle like this.

00:59:21.380 --> 00:59:24.900
And your job is to move these
into a target state.

00:59:24.900 --> 00:59:27.730
And so to get over to here,
you've got to move the blue

00:59:27.730 --> 00:59:32.160
guy over here and whatever, in
a different number of moves.

00:59:32.160 --> 00:59:34.310
That's planning ahead
and problem solving.

00:59:34.310 --> 00:59:36.790
Patients with frontal lobe
lesions make many mistakes on

00:59:36.790 --> 00:59:39.470
these kinds of tasks.

00:59:39.470 --> 00:59:41.210
So the last thing I want to
talk is a little bit about

00:59:41.210 --> 00:59:44.390
Phineas Gage kind of lesions.

00:59:44.390 --> 00:59:49.120
And we'll get in a moment to a
comment about serial killers.

00:59:49.120 --> 00:59:51.120
So Phineas Gage had
this huge injury.

00:59:51.120 --> 00:59:52.320
We talked about him
already in the

00:59:52.320 --> 00:59:55.730
ventromedial prefrontal cortex.

00:59:55.730 --> 00:59:58.090
There's some other patients
who have orbitofrontal

00:59:58.090 --> 00:59:59.030
lesions, who have
been studied.

00:59:59.030 --> 01:00:00.210
And let me tell you
a little bit about

01:00:00.210 --> 01:00:02.050
what's known about them.

01:00:02.050 --> 01:00:03.590
And I can tell you this is the
part of the brain that's been

01:00:03.590 --> 01:00:07.180
most implicated in psychopaths,
some of whom turn

01:00:07.180 --> 01:00:10.110
out to be these serial
killers.

01:00:10.110 --> 01:00:12.360
One measure they've used in
these experiments is galvanic

01:00:12.360 --> 01:00:13.250
skin response.

01:00:13.250 --> 01:00:14.360
That's the kind of
stuff they use in

01:00:14.360 --> 01:00:15.730
polygraphs, lie detectors.

01:00:15.730 --> 01:00:19.220
They put them on your skin and
what they measure is responses

01:00:19.220 --> 01:00:22.190
that are related to
sweat glands.

01:00:22.190 --> 01:00:26.430
So it's a measure of emotional
reactivity, basically.

01:00:26.430 --> 01:00:28.020
Here's a really interesting
thing.

01:00:28.020 --> 01:00:30.820
If we measure your galvanic skin
response and we show you

01:00:30.820 --> 01:00:33.320
faces of people you know, family
members, friends, and

01:00:33.320 --> 01:00:36.730
so on, versus people you don't
know, you get a galvanic skin

01:00:36.730 --> 01:00:38.510
response for the people
you know, because

01:00:38.510 --> 01:00:39.780
they matter to you.

01:00:39.780 --> 01:00:44.030
It's an emotional response,
versus faces you don't know.

01:00:44.030 --> 01:00:46.350
You even get that kind of
strikingly in several studies

01:00:46.350 --> 01:00:47.850
in patients with
prosopagnosia.

01:00:47.850 --> 01:00:50.280
So we talked about those
patients who can't recognize

01:00:50.280 --> 01:00:51.890
people by their faces.

01:00:51.890 --> 01:00:54.620
But something in them still
recognizes who's

01:00:54.620 --> 01:00:57.120
familiar and who's not.

01:00:57.120 --> 01:01:00.030
Even if they can't tell you,
that's my mother or that's my

01:01:00.030 --> 01:01:02.980
father or that's my brother,
their galvanic skin response

01:01:02.980 --> 01:01:06.210
is a pretty good response.

01:01:06.210 --> 01:01:07.520
Patients with orbitofrontal
lesions

01:01:07.520 --> 01:01:09.140
are exactly the opposite.

01:01:09.140 --> 01:01:11.830
When they're shown pictures of
family members and friends,

01:01:11.830 --> 01:01:15.280
they have no more of a response
in the sweat glands,

01:01:15.280 --> 01:01:17.300
in the autonomic nervous system,
than they do for

01:01:17.300 --> 01:01:19.120
absolute strangers.

01:01:19.120 --> 01:01:22.220
And you might intuitively
imagine that it's pretty easy

01:01:22.220 --> 01:01:25.730
to lie and deceive your friends
and family, if they

01:01:25.730 --> 01:01:27.420
don't mean to you anything more

01:01:27.420 --> 01:01:28.670
than an absolute stranger.

01:01:30.890 --> 01:01:32.640
No galvanic response
to emotional

01:01:32.640 --> 01:01:33.990
versus neutral pictures.

01:01:33.990 --> 01:01:36.420
And so these patients seem to
have this disconnection

01:01:36.420 --> 01:01:37.660
between thought and emotion.

01:01:37.660 --> 01:01:39.160
They know who the person is.

01:01:39.160 --> 01:01:41.620
But they don't have an emotional
response of any kind

01:01:41.620 --> 01:01:43.460
to that person.

01:01:43.460 --> 01:01:46.020
And here's one clever experiment
that shows some of

01:01:46.020 --> 01:01:47.560
the consequence of that.

01:01:47.560 --> 01:01:49.780
So this is work from Damasio
and his colleagues.

01:01:49.780 --> 01:01:51.670
So they took a couple
of these patients.

01:01:51.670 --> 01:01:53.020
There's not that many of them.

01:01:53.020 --> 01:01:55.160
And they put them into an
experiment where you could

01:01:55.160 --> 01:01:56.410
pick from two decks.

01:01:56.410 --> 01:01:58.100
One deck has a low immediate
reward, but

01:01:58.100 --> 01:01:59.860
positive long-term rewards.

01:01:59.860 --> 01:02:02.410
It's a little bit like studying
a lot, and hoping it

01:02:02.410 --> 01:02:03.930
all pays off.

01:02:03.930 --> 01:02:06.490
And another one is high
immediate rewards, but higher

01:02:06.490 --> 01:02:07.270
long-term losses.

01:02:07.270 --> 01:02:10.860
Like not studying has some
unpleasant consequences.

01:02:10.860 --> 01:02:12.040
So two decks of cards.

01:02:12.040 --> 01:02:15.570
And you don't know this, but you
just quickly discover that

01:02:15.570 --> 01:02:21.120
Pile A, you get the occasional
$50, but you often lose $100.

01:02:21.120 --> 01:02:25.460
But Pile B, you get the thrill
of the $100 loss, but you

01:02:25.460 --> 01:02:27.730
often lose $1,000.

01:02:27.730 --> 01:02:30.310
So they're kind of pitting
against each other, the thrill

01:02:30.310 --> 01:02:36.500
of the $100 win, versus the
certain doom of the quick

01:02:36.500 --> 01:02:38.450
thrill pile.

01:02:38.450 --> 01:02:41.510
You get the quick thrill,
but it will doom you.

01:02:41.510 --> 01:02:43.270
So what do typical people do?

01:02:43.270 --> 01:02:45.480
After a little while, they
figure out well, Pile B is

01:02:45.480 --> 01:02:46.680
pretty fun when I
get the $100.

01:02:46.680 --> 01:02:49.270
But it beats me up a lot in the
long term, so they go for

01:02:49.270 --> 01:02:50.180
Pile A.

01:02:50.180 --> 01:02:51.650
Orbitofrontal patients don't.

01:02:51.650 --> 01:02:54.470
They go for that one-time
thrill, over any long-term

01:02:54.470 --> 01:02:56.720
consequences.

01:02:56.720 --> 01:02:59.830
As interesting as that, if you
measure the galvanic skin

01:02:59.830 --> 01:03:05.650
response, for control people,
typical people, when they go

01:03:05.650 --> 01:03:10.040
for the risky pile, their heart
is pounding, their hands

01:03:10.040 --> 01:03:10.230
are sweating.

01:03:10.230 --> 01:03:13.390
And they go, I'm going to
walk on the wild side.

01:03:13.390 --> 01:03:15.320
Back to the save file, mostly.

01:03:15.320 --> 01:03:17.340
No galvanic skin response
for the patients with

01:03:17.340 --> 01:03:17.690
orbitofrontal lesions.

01:03:17.690 --> 01:03:18.117
Yeah?

01:03:18.117 --> 01:03:20.370
AUDIENCE: Do people
get the lesions

01:03:20.370 --> 01:03:22.930
after reaching adulthood?

01:03:22.930 --> 01:03:23.640
PROFESSOR: So this
is interesting.

01:03:23.640 --> 01:03:26.620
I'm going to come to
this in a moment.

01:03:26.620 --> 01:03:29.330
Actually literally, absolutely
right now.

01:03:29.330 --> 01:03:31.680
Same pattern for people who
have these injuries at 15

01:03:31.680 --> 01:03:34.500
months or three months, as
happens in adulthood.

01:03:34.500 --> 01:03:36.590
Now, we don't know if
that's everybody.

01:03:36.590 --> 01:03:39.290
But these are patients who
came forth with problems.

01:03:39.290 --> 01:03:40.800
So this is a little bit like,
we don't know if there are a

01:03:40.800 --> 01:03:42.860
